bug.short_desc: An app loses it's icon from switching from gnome to gnome classic and back
bug.cf_doc_type: If docs needed, set a value

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1171552 How google drive app looks like after switching between gnome and gnome classic and back.
Description of problem: After logging out and logging in and changing from gnome to gnome classic desktop, an app loses it's icon, namely google drive.
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable):
How reproducible: To be seen, most likely always
Steps to Reproduce: 1. Install the google drive web app from the software center 2. log out from gnome 3. change to gnome classic - log in. 4. log out again and log in to gnome.
Actual results: the google drive app is there and works normally but the icon is lost and it appears like a black square.
Expected results: changing between default desktop environments should not mess with app icons, or at least icons should revert back when going back to the default desktop environment for Fedora.
Additional info:
Created attachment 1171553 I just noticed two google drives as well in the software center after the icon went missing.

Created attachment 1171555 After uninstalling google drive app, the icons is lost from the software center as well.
After the google drive icon disappeared in my desktop because of me switching between gnome classic and gnome default, I decided to uninstall the icon. It uninstalled ok, I closed gnome-software and then re-opened in order to install it. I noticed that the google drive app icon went missing now from gnome-software as well.
And I also noticed that other web apps now miss their icons too in the gnome-software center, such as google talk google maps google plus and others.
Created attachment 1171556 other gnome-software web - apps lost their icons as well.
A restart of the system brought all icons back. Now I will test switching desktop environments again.
After the restart icons don't go missing again even if after switching desktop environments. The bug is not always reproducible.
